label chapter8:

    # [Scene: Lantern Lighthouse | Dusk]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, rising acoustic strings — warm and expectant]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Crackle of fire, distant gulls, soft murmur of voices]
    "You stand where the path narrows toward the beacon. Salt spray clings to the air: metallic on your tongue, bright in your nose. The lighthouse is a penumbra of shadow and light; its paint peels like old promises, but tonight its beam is only a witness, not a judge."
    "Rosa kneels at the edge of the sand, hands deep in a tote of paper lanterns, fingers stained dark with ink and soil. Niko leans against a rusted piling, hoodie zipped against the wind, making a"
    "slow, steady list aloud so no one forgets a single detail. Tomas kneels beside you, his tablet off to the side for once — tonight he brought a thermos and a patience you can hold onto."
    "You feel the crowd as a living thing: compost-streaked boots, a child's breath fogging in the cold, a woman with a placard reading 'Our Shore, Our Vote' folded against her chest. The community has come because"
    "the choice before you wasn't a municipal checkbox; it is a map of all the small places that keep people rooted."
    show rosa_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_marin "We light them for what we want to keep. Not just buildings—stories, shellfish beds, the corner where Mateo learned to tie knots. Everyone gets a chance to name something."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "We make it visible,' you say. Your voice sounds different in the open, steadier. 'We show the council what 'community' looks like when it's made by hands and not promises."
    show tomas_herrera at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_herrera "And we make it legible. If we can translate the technical into something people feel in their bones, they'll carry it to the polls."
    hide rosa_marin
    show niko_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_alvarez "Legible, like... infographics shaped like bread? I'm in."
    "The group laughs, a small buoyant sound. A laugh that doesn't deny fear so much as flings it a rope."
    "Lena steps forward, her recorder humming like a curious insect. 'I'll run a piece tonight. Bonfires, the referendum pitch, community voices. People need to see this is about living, not just property lines.'"
    "You watch her frame the scene with words, and some private certainty settles: telling the story is as crucial as getting the signatures. If you can make the referendum feel like a neighbor's backyard, it stops being an abstract ballot and becomes rescue."

    menu:
        "Let Rosa light first and speak":
            "Rosa rises carefully, lantern in hand. Her voice is thin but carries; she names a list of small, sacred places and people, and the circle tightens. You feel the group's breath sync with hers."
        "Open with your own brief speech":
            "You step to the center, tone steady. You say why the referendum matters: living shorelines, local stewardship, long-term safety. Heads nod; someone shouts an assent, the fire leans toward you as if warming itself on your words."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."
    "Rosa: (after a pause) 'We will canvas tomorrow at dawn. Niko—routes. Lena—stories. Tomas, can your team fold the policy sheets into an accessible two-page? Not jargon. Not platitudes. What people can use.'"

    tomas_herrera "Already on it. I'm taking the pilot model and making page one a literal map—'If you live here, this is what happens in year one, year five.' No acronyms, no committee names. Just people, places, timelines."
    "You feel his competence like a soft weight at your side. It's a new kind of intimacy, built from shared urgency and problem-solving. You want to both hold it and not smother it in your fear of compromise."
    "Elys' name comes up in a ripple — not from the crowd, but from the static in your pocket. Lena's tablet buzzes; she checks it with a tight look."
    hide mara_voss
    show lena_park at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lena_park "Elys released a statement two hours ago. She's framing the referendum as 'procedurally risky' and offering an alternative 'fast-track redevelopment' pitch. Her campaign is putting out targeted ads along the waterfront."
    "You feel a small, familiar flare of anger—an animal sound. Then you exhale. The lighthouse beam sweeps like a patient eye across the horizon. Anger is useful in short bursts; tonight you need endurance."
    hide tomas_herrera
    show mara_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "Then we make endurance loud. We double the canvassers. We make every story a beacon."
    "Rosa: (nods) 'And we anchor it with truth. Remember the wetland maps from elders. Remember what the shore used to be. People respond to memory.'"

    niko_alvarez "Also, I can put up posters on the promenade. Simple, clear. QR codes for Lena's pieces."
    hide niko_alvarez
    show tomas_herrera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_herrera "We'll run training for volunteers so they can answer basic questions — safety, cost, timeline. Confusion is the enemy; clarity is our scaffold."

    lena_park "I'll run an audio postcard series — quick five-minute interviews with residents. Intimacy beats anger in the long run."
    "You close your eyes for a second and picture the weeks to come: door-to-door conversations at 6 a.m., posters flapping in rain, children handing out stickers with little tidal symbols. It's not glamorous. It's a grind."
    "And it's the only thing that has ever changed policy in this town without letting profit write the margins."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden at the Old Textile Mill | Early Morning]
    hide lena_park
    hide mara_voss
    hide tomas_herrera

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Light, optimistic piano with a steady rhythm]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rustle of paper, soft footsteps on rooftop gravel, distant city hum]
    "You climb up the iron staircase with a tote of flyers. The rooftop smells like soil, citrus, and a hint of diesel from early delivery trucks. The beds are lined in neat rows; dew beads like pearls along the leaves. Volunteers unpack sandwiches and markers, folding policy into human sentences."
    "Tomas Herrera is mid-demonstration, using a cardboard cutout to show sea-level scenarios. He smiles when he sees you, the kind of smile that says he trusts you to run when he plans."
    show tomas_herrera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_herrera "Think of it like a tidechart for your own block. If we can show what happens at high tide in five years versus twenty, people stop arguing in abstract and start defending their kitchens."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "And if they ask about jobs or housing—' (you gesture toward the skyline) '—we can't pretend those aren't valid concerns. We show them how the pilot protects livelihoods and creates jobs through restoration work."
    "Niko hands you a stack of canvassing sheets. 'Route alpha,' he says. 'You and Rosa take the Promenade stretch. I'll take the marina section with two others. We hit the playground at midday.'"
    "Rosa: (packing lantern strings) 'I'll go with you. There are corners I want to point out—places that are easy to name. Stories open hands.'"
    "Lena: (checking her recorder) 'I want a quiet minute with each of you today — to capture the why. Not statements. The why.'"
    "You feel suddenly very mortal and very invincible at once. The thing you're asking everyone to do—to turn emotion into civic muscle—feels daunting and yet perfectly doable. You remember the day you lost your family's house"
    "to a surge: how small decisions accumulated into catastrophe. That memory sharpens your urgency, but it doesn't freeze you. It becomes fuel."
    "A new conundrum presents itself: Tomas has designed two versions of the handout. One leans into technical clarity (charts, timelines), the other into personal stories and images. Both are true; they will appeal to different people. There's no wrong answer, only different doors."

    menu:
        "Distribute the technical-first handouts to older residents and the personal stories to the young":
            "You and Tomas split the stack that way. At the next block, an elderly man leans in to study a chart and later thanks you because it answered the 'how' he was worrying about. A teenager grips a personal story and texts a friend. You watch both conversations bloom."
        "Mix them together into the same handout — a story and the chart side-by-side":
            "You fold the materials so each handout carries both heart and scaffold. People stop to point at both the map and the family photos. A little girl traces the chart with her finger, eyes wide, and asks what happens next. The combination seems to hold more hands."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."

    tomas_herrera "We should rehearse answers to the predictable pushbacks — cost, timeline, private property concerns. If someone brings up Elys' ads, steer them to the fact sheets and to Lena's stories."

    mara_voss "And remind people it's a referendum. This is their power. We give them a chance to choose what the shore is for."

    "Niko (juggling some pins)" "Also, leave them a sticker. People love stickers."
    "Lena crouches down in front of you; for a moment the rooftop pauses. Her recorder blinks. 'Mara,' she says, voice low, 'why are you doing this? Really.'"

    mara_voss "Because if we do not try, then the shore will be decided by the people with the loudest money and the softest promises. We have soil, knowledge, children, and time. We deserve to show up with them."
    show lena_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lena_park "Good. Say that to the mic."
    "You let the rooftop air take your words and send them out like a kite. They land on faces, and faces return them, steadier, wanting."
    # [Scene: Harbor Promenade | Late Afternoon]
    hide tomas_herrera
    hide mara_voss
    hide lena_park

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Building chorus — light percussion and hopeful strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Footsteps, snippets of conversation, distant diesel hums, a vendor calling out]
    "The promenade smells like wet wood and fried dough. The sky hangs in a thin linen of cloud; light refracts off puddles in a thousand little mirrors. You move through the crowd, a map in one"
    "hand and a stack of leaflets in the other. Small bonfires have been set safely in metal drums near the benches; people gather, share tea, name the places they want protected."
    "You stop to speak with a fisherman whose hands still smell of tar. He studies the flyer with the map and points to a shallow inlet."

    "Fisherman" "If you can keep that eelgrass, we'll still have a living bay. These kids here...' (he jerks his chin toward a group building a sandbar model) '—they learn from it. There's more than money in that."
    show mara_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "Then we'll put the eelgrass restoration in the pilot. We'll make it part of the jobs plan."
    "He nods slowly, surprised in a good way. 'That's what I needed to hear.'"
    "Across the promenade, you see the flash of a campaign van — Elys Reed's logo crisp against a slate backdrop. A volunteer hands out glossy brochures that look like magazine ads: slick renderings of glass-front buildings"
    "and raised promenades, the kind of images that can feel like a balm to anxious voters. You feel the old instinct — to shout facts into the air — but instead you count breaths and approach"
    "with an invitation."
    "Mara Voss: (to one of Elys' canvassers) 'Have you walked the shoreline with our team? We have elders ready to show you where the water used to come.'"
    "Canvasser: (politely) 'We're with the redevelopment campaign. We appreciate what the grassroots is doing, but we think the town needs jobs and quick action.'"

    mara_voss "We all want jobs. We just disagree on whose hands build them. Come by tomorrow. Talk to Rosa. Hear what 'jobs' could mean if they restore the shore instead of paving it."
    "Canvasser: (a flicker of something — curiosity?) 'I'll—I'll think about it.'"
    "The exchange is small. That smallness is everything. You trade a pamphlet for a pause in someone's march toward certainty."
    "Niko returns with news: the promontory turnout is higher than expected; Lena is streaming live and people are sharing their stories. Tomas Herrera thumbs through messages on his tablet and finds one that matters: a neighborhood"
    "association is willing to sponsor a late-night vigil on the promenade on the weekend, turning the grassroots energy into a civic calendar."
    show tomas_herrera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_herrera "This is the momentum. But Elys' team is scaling their messaging too. We're in a sprint."
    "You feel the word sprint like a cup of cold water. Your muscles remember threshold toughness from planting days. This will be long, but the steps are clear."
    "Elys Reed herself is not in the crowd; her face appears instead in a projected pamphlet video, voice measured and polished. Lena's live stream captures the contrast: your hands dirty from soil; the ad's set glossy"
    "and stylized. The juxtaposition draws a line in people's minds — one of intimacy and one of image."
    "Lena: (leaning into the camera) 'They're telling stories over there. We're telling our lives.'"
    "The crowd cheers, soft and immediate. A child runs past with a sticker shaped like a tide gauge, and someone starts a chant that is more a rhythm than a slogan — 'shore for all' — and the sound rolls like a tide."
    "You find a place on the bench and let yourself feel the current of proximity. People are showing up with their memories, their expectations, their hunger for stability. The referendum has done something you did not"
    "quite imagine when you first signed the petition: it has made civic engagement tactile. It's a series of small bonfires, and each one throws enough light to read by."
    "Mara Voss: (to Tomas Herrera, quietly) 'Are we ready for when the countercampaign goes harder? For when they frame this as risky?'"

    tomas_herrera "We already have answers. We have elders, scientists, and people who remember what the shore can be. We have Lena, who knows how to make a microphone feel like a neighbor. We have Niko. We have you."
    "The list of supporters is not a clause; it's a spine. Every name is a name you would carry into a storm."
    "Elys Reed's campaign ramps up its visuals along the waterfront: glossy renderings, a staged ribbon-cutting promise for future 'resilient housing.' But as the sun slips and the promenade cools, your lanterns outnumber the polished signs. People"
    "gather around the metal drum fires, singing quietly, passing a flask, exchanging the small stories that do the heavy civic lifting."
    "You think of the weeks ahead like a tide chart: rising effort, planned rests, waves of canvassing, nights of vigil. The sprint is daunting, but within it, you find a strange, steady joy — the work you love in full view, shoulder to shoulder with people who will show up."
    "Niko: (clapping you on the shoulder) 'Tomorrow we hit the neighborhoods. Will you come stand with Rosa at the schoolyard at ten? Kids hand out stickers—it's good optics and honest work.'"

    mara_voss "I'll be there. We'll bring the maps and make them personal."
    show lena_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lena_park "Tonight's piece goes up after the vigil. I want an opening line that isn't about politics but about what people are keeping."

    "You close your eyes briefly and assemble the line in your head" "We light these fires for everything we intend to keep."
    "A boy drops a tiny tidechart sticker at your feet and looks up with wide eyes. You crouch, pick it up, and press it into your palm. The paper is thin and warm from his hand."
    "Mara Voss: (to yourself) 'This is who votes.'"
    "The lanterns rise. The promenade hums. Somewhere beyond the puddled concrete, cranes silhouette new development. They are not the story tonight."
    "You look toward the horizon where the lighthouse is a faint white tooth against dusk and feel something like a current under your feet—steady, gathering power. This is the beginning of a civic season, and the referendum is the drumbeat."
    "You inhale the wet air and carry the sound of low, hopeful voices with you—into canvassing, into training, into the long nights where stories are translated into ballots."
    hide mara_voss
    hide tomas_herrera
    hide lena_park

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings swell in hopeful ascent, then resolve into a quiet, anticipatory chord]
    "You are not naive. You know the opposition will sharpen its tools, that messaging will harden into bullets. But you also know how to make people feel ownership. You know how to put soil and hand and memory into a ballot box."
    "You stand on the promenade a moment longer, feeling the warmth from a drum fire on your face. You feel Tomas' hand briefly on your shoulder—a steady, almost invisible anchor. You look at the lanterns, at"
    "the faces in the glow, and you feel the tide of people moving in the direction you've chosen."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single ascending chord lingers; the night air is full of possibility]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg

